The proper scope of the power to subpoena documents depends on what has been called the “substantive” and “adjectival” relevance of the information sought. Substantive relevance refers to the direct proof of factual issues in the proceedings. Adjectival relevance refers to the capacity of the documents sought to support a conclusion or proposition that has an arguable relevance to the proceedings: Cosco Holdings Pty Ltd v Cmr of Taxation (1997) 37 ATR 432;  BC9707273 . The width of that description necessarily means there is no implied requirement that the documents sought should be intended to be tendered in evidence, nor even that they be admissible: National Employers Mutual General Insurance Association Ltd v Waind and Hill [1978] 1 NSWLR 372 . Adjectival relevance is often contrasted with “fishing” (see 
[33.4.20]
) to indicate the distinction between the permissible and impermissible scope of a subpoena for production. It is intended to highlight the requirement for a positive satisfaction that the documents sought are likely to inform the proper determination of the issues in the proceedings. A subpoena may be set aside if it requires the production of documents with insufficient apparent relevance to the proceedings: Trade Practices Commission v Arnotts Ltd (No 2) (1989) 21 FCR 306; 88 ALR 90;  BC8908420 ; Hatton v A-G (Cth) (2000) 26 Fam LR 570; 158 FLR 31; FLC ¶93-038; [2000] FamCA 892 .

Where a third person produces documents in answer to a subpoena issued by one of the parties, and does not oppose their inspection, the other parties to the proceedings will ordinarily have a limited basis to object to their inspection. This ordinary position is a consequence of the likelihood that the third party’s ownership or possession of the documents will often be inconsistent with the ability of a party to assert any relevant interest in relation to them. However, the validity of this general proposition in any particular case must depend on the particular circumstances. A party may resist (on any of the grounds referred to in 
[33.9.5]
) inspection being granted whenever it is able to establish a proper basis for so doing (for example, legal professional privilege): Southern Pacific Hotel Services Inc v Southern Pacific Hotel Corp Ltd [1984] 1 NSWLR 710 .
